\section*{Process Oriented Theories}

These theories have focussed on intellectual processes-the pattern of thinking that people use when they reason and solve problems. These theorists prefer to use the term cognitive processes in place of intelligence. They are often more interested in how people solve problems and how many get the right solution. They have focussed on the development of cognitive abilities. Piaget's work is a significant contribution in this area (see Chapter 12). He viewed intelligence as an adaptive process that involves interplay of biological maturation and interaction with environment.

